[1] _Blueberry scorch virus_, _Blueberry shock virus_ - USA (Michigan)
[2] Valdensinia leaf drop - Canada (Nova Scotia, New Brunswick), USA (Maine)

******
[1] _Blueberry scorch virus_, _Blueberry shock virus_ - USA (Michigan)
Date: Fri 31 Jul 2009
Source: Michigan Farmer [edited]
<http://michiganfarmer.com/story.aspx?s=25239&c=9>


New blueberry diseases confirmed in Michigan
--------------------------------------------
Michigan Department of Agriculture [MDA] Director Don Koivisto today
[31 Jul 2009] announced 2 exotic blueberry diseases have been
identified in Michigan for the 1st time -- blueberry shock and
blueberry scorch. Both viral plant diseases have the potential to
cause significant losses to blueberry producers. MDA and Michigan
State University [MSU] officials are aggressively implementing a
response plan to eradicate these diseases.

Michigan is the nation's number one blueberry producer with
blueberries valued at USD 124 million in 2008. The MDA has been
watching for these diseases due to their presence in certain West
Coast and mid-Atlantic states and taking steps to prevent them from
entering the state through issuance of an external quarantine in 2002
and through routine sampling. "Although not totally unexpected, we
are very disappointed these 2 serious diseases have been identified
in southwest Michigan," Koivisto says.

Annemiek Schilder, MSU, was part of the team that identified
blueberry shock in a research plot in Fennville. Blueberry scorch
virus was discovered at a private farm in west Michigan. The infected
plants have been destroyed and MDA agents are testing adjacent areas
to verify blueberry scorch disease has not spread.

There are no known cures for either of these plant diseases. "We
believe that both diseases are restricted to small areas and can be
eradicated," Schilder says. "But buying plants from a nursery selling
virus-tested plants is the best way to prevent further infection
because both plant diseases can be spread via infected cuttings."

--
