[2] Valdensinia leaf drop - Canada (Nova Scotia, New Brunswick), USA (Maine)
Date: Mon 27 Jul 2009
Source: Brattleboro Reformer and The Associated Press (AP) [edited]
<http://www.reformer.com/localnews/ci_12934327>


Vermont agriculture experts are keeping their fingers crossed
concerning a new deadly fungus that is threatening Maine's
blueberries. The cool, wet weather this summer [2009] is causing an
explosion in plant diseases that experts say are always around, but
are usually kept at bay by dry, warm periods. The coming weeks could
make the difference between salvaging the harvest and losing entire crops.

Scientists from the University of Maine this week confirmed
valdensinia leaf spot on wild blueberry plants in Sumner, Maine. The
deadly fungus devastated crops in Nova Scotia and New Brunswick and
blueberry pathologist Seanna Annis said the disease could destroy
plants this summer [2009] and next [2010] in what is one of Maine's
most important agricultural products.

[Byline: Howard Weiss-Tisman]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[_Blueberry scorch virus_ (BlScV; genus _Carlavirus_) has been
described as a heterogeneous collection of strains, including the
strains associated with blueberry scorch on the west coast of North
America and others associated with Sheep Pen Hill disease on the east
coast. The virus appears to be transmitted by aphids and by grafting.

_Blueberry shock virus_ (B1ShV; genus _Ilarvirus_) was first detected
in the Pacific Northwest region of North America. The virus is pollen
borne and also transmitted by grafting and mechanical inoculation.

Blueberry scorch and shock disease symptoms are similar and may
include leaf scorching, dieback of shoot tips and twigs, and flower
blight. Fruit production and shoot growth are seriously reduced. Both
viruses spread quickly through a crop from the point of 1st
infection. Certified virus free planting material is essential in the
management of these viruses.

Valdensinia leaf drop (or leaf spot) of blueberries (_Vaccinium_
species) is caused by the fungus _Valdensinia heterodoxa_. Severe
losses have been reported in Canadian blueberry plantings through
rapid defoliation and failure of berries to mature in size.
Fungicides may be effective in suppressing the disease, but are not
able to eradicate it from a field.

For more information on these diseases see links to fact sheets listed below.

